  <mainDescription>OMG defines the Business Motivation Model as:&amp;nbsp;&lt;br />&#xD;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;br />&#xD;
“[A] specification [that] provides a scheme or structure for developing, communicating, and managing business plans in an&#xD;
organized manner. Specifically, the Business Motivation Model does all of the following: &#xD;
&lt;ul>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        It identifies factors that motivate the establishing of business plans.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        It identifies and defines the elements of business plans.&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
    &lt;li>&#xD;
        It indicates how all these factors and elements inter-relate.”&amp;nbsp; (&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.omg.org/spec/#BM&quot;&#xD;
        target=&quot;_blank&quot;>OMG 2010&lt;/a>)&#xD;
    &lt;/li>&#xD;
&lt;/ul>&#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    Other definitions broaden this concept and meaning: “The Enterprise Business Motivation Model (EBMM) is a conceptual&#xD;
    information model, described using UML, that captures the relationships between the business drivers, business models,&#xD;
    business processes, and business units that make up a typical commercial organization (&lt;a&#xD;
    href=&quot;http://motivationmodel.com/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;>Malik 2009&lt;/a>).” The OMG definition has been around for a number of&#xD;
    years; however there is no consensus in this evolving area.&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br /></mainDescription>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ContentDescription>
